                <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:anchor>2456</fr:anchor>
                    <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-9.1.2</fr:addr>
                    <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-9.1.2.xml</fr:route>
                    <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
                    <fr:authors />
                    <fr:number>9.1.2</fr:number>
                    <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-9.1</fr:parent>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> be an algebraic group (over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>), and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> a (algebraic) principal homogeneous space with group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> over a scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.
    Then the morphism
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       [P]\colon \operatorname {H}^\bullet (\mathrm {B}_G)=\operatorname {H}^\bullet (\mathrm {B}_{\bullet  G})       \to  \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X)     ]]></fr:tex>
    is a morphism of mixed Hodge structures.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2438</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#237</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-237.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-9.1.2</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>This follows from the definition (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.3.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.3.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="6.1.3.1" />) of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[P]]]></fr:tex> and from functoriality (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.3.4" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.3.4.xml" taxon="Definition" number="8.3.4" />).</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
                  <fr:backmatter />
                </fr:tree>
                <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:anchor>2457</fr:anchor>
                    <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-9.1.3</fr:addr>
                    <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-9.1.3.xml</fr:route>
                    <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
                    <fr:authors />
                    <fr:number>9.1.3</fr:number>
                    <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-9.1</fr:parent>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <fr:p>The characteristic classes, in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^{2n}(S)]]></fr:tex>, of a (algebraic) principal homogeneous space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, with structure group a linear group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>, are pure of type <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(n,n)]]></fr:tex>: they come from morphisms <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}(-n)\to \operatorname {H}^{2n}(S,\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                  <fr:backmatter />
                </fr:tree>
                <fr:p>In the particular case where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is smooth and quasi-projective, we know that the characteristic classes of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> are even algebraic, i.e. in the image of the Chow ring <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\otimes \mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
